(468454, 13577, 468430, 'Sand', 15746, '', 1417846530, 'Now that I''ve had to waste around 50 calories writing the reply to Kid''s questions, I would write some smallish interesting stuff.\n\nThe most powerful combat strike a human being can make, is a boxer''s punch. No shaolin master''s kick or kickboxer''s kick or any such thing even comes close to the fully stretched punch of a boxer.\n\nThe faster combat strike a human being can make, is a kungfu master''s open hand strike. Kungfu masters usually emphasize on a strike being as fast as a snake''s strike, but in fact a kungfu master''s hand strike travels nearly [B][/B]times as fast as a snake''s strike. When the National Geographic team analysed and compared the speed of a kungfu master to that of a snake''s strike, the kungfu practitioner was shocked. "I thought I could hardly match the speed of a striking snake, and that too, would take years of practice!" He said. It does not however means that a snake''s striking speed is to be ridiculed. Very few other martial arts schools can attain a snake''s striking speed.\n\nAll in all, the  most hard-hitting of all martial arts is Muay Thai. With some modifications (aimed at making it more western and suitable for ring matches than real life street fights) it is called Kickboxing. Muay Thai incorporates the most advanced methods for effectively using knee and elbow strikes. It is also the most useful type of martial arts for street fights where no rules apply.\n\nThe most elegant of all martial arts is Capoeiria. Invented by Angolan slaves as a means to combine combat moves with dancing, the effort resulted in the most graceful of all martial arts ever. The home of Capoeiria is south america.', 1, 1, '182.189.129.151', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 0, 0),
